      "title": "Introduction",
      "description": "# Introduction\n\nAll HTML documents have the same basic structure or boilerplate that needs to be in place before anything useful can be done. In this lesson, we will explore the different parts of this boilerplate and see how they fit together.\n\n## In this lesson, you'll learn:\n\n- What is an HTML file?\n- Parts of an HTML file"
    },
    {
      "title": "HTML files",
      "description": "# HTML files\nAn HTML file is a type of file that helps tell a web browser how to read and display content. These instructions are called **markup**, and the way we mark up web content is by using **HTML tags**. \n\nBrowsers know files are HTML files because they use the `.html` file extension. Each file makes one page on a website. You can name HTML files anything you want as long as you don't include spaces or special characters in the name.\n\nIn your explorer panel, inside your `src` folder, you should see an HTML file. We call this file `index.html` because it is the first page of our site. This is now standard practice in the web, and is a nod to when web servers used to display the \"index\" of the files in a folder so you could navigate between documents.\n\nIn the next step, we'll review what's in a standard HTML file, and then learn to add our own content."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/index.html",
      "description": "# The Doctype\n\nEvery HTML page starts with a doctype declaration. The doctype’s purpose is to tell the browser what version of HTML it should use to render the document. The latest version of HTML is HTML5, and the doctype for that version is simply `<!DOCTYPE html>`.\n\nThe doctype is always the first line in the file. Never put it anywhere else in the HTML file.",
      "line": 1,
      "title": "The Doctype",
